Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code for your `EventProcessor`.

## Pattern Inventory

| API | Location | Pattern | Replacement |
|-----|----------|---------|-------------|
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `Stop()` | Blocking call interruption | `CancellationToken` signaling |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Cancellable work loop fallback | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` | `RunLoop()` | Blocking call interruption | `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with `token.WaitHandle` |
| `while (true)` | `RunLoop()` | Cancellable work loop | `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)` |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new();
    private readonly object _lock = new();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;
        var handles = new[] { _newEvent, token.WaitHandle };

        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // WaitAny returns index: 0 = new event, 1 = cancellation
            int signaled = WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);
            if (signaled == 1)
                break; // cancellation requested

            _newEvent.Reset();

            // Drain all queued items, not just one — the original code
            // had a bug where signals could be lost if multiple Enqueue
            // calls happened before WaitOne returned.
            while (true)
            {
                string? item;
                lock (_lock)
                {
                    if (_queue.Count == 0) break;
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
                }
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();       // wakes WaitAny via token.WaitHandle
        _thread?.Join(5000); // wait for graceful exit
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

## Key Changes Explained

1. **`Thread.Abort()` / `Thread.Interrupt()` → `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()`** — Cooperative cancellation replaces forcible termination. `Cancel()` signals `token.WaitHandle`, which unblocks `WaitAny` immediately.

2. **`ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` → `WaitHandle.WaitAny(event, token.WaitHandle)`** — The thread now wakes on *either* a new event or cancellation. This eliminates the need for `Interrupt()` to poke a blocked thread.

3. **`while (true)` → `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)`** — The loop checks for cancellation each iteration.

4. **Added `IDisposable`** — `CancellationTokenSource` and `ManualResetEvent` must be disposed to avoid timer/handle leaks.

## Bug Fixed in Original Code

The original had a race condition: two rapid `Enqueue` calls could coalesce into one `Set()` signal, but `RunLoop` only dequeued one item per wake-up. The migrated version drains all items each time.

## Pitfalls to Watch

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| **Not passing `CancellationToken` into `Handle()`** | If `Handle()` does long-running or blocking work, cancellation stalls until it returns. Pass the token through and check it inside. |
| **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks internal timers and registered callbacks. Always `using` or explicit `Dispose()`. |
| **Assuming cancellation is instant** | It only takes effect at the next `WaitAny` / `IsCancellationRequested` check. If `Handle()` runs for 30 seconds, `Stop()` waits up to 30 seconds. |
| **Calling `Stop()` twice** | Safe here — `Cancel()` is idempotent and `Join` on an already-exited thread returns immediately. |
